\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Created by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enid_Blyton"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Enid Blyton}}, Noddy first appeared in the\'a0
\f1\i Sunday Graphic
\f0\i0 \'a0on 5 June 1949, the same year as Blyton's first daily Noddy\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comic_strip"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 strip}}\'a0for the London\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evening_Standard"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\i \cf4 \strokec4 Evening Standard}}.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noddy_(character)#cite_note-EBSChrono-1"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf4 \super \strokec4 [1]}}\'a0In November that year\'a0
\f1\i Noddy Goes to Toyland
\f0\i0 , the first of at least two dozen books in the series, was published. The idea was conceived by one of Blyton's publishers, Sampson, Low, Marston and Company, who in 1949 arranged a meeting between Blyton and the Dutch illustrator\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harmsen_van_der_Beek"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Harmsen van der Beek}}. Despite having to communicate via an interpreter, he provided some initial sketches of how Toyland and its characters would be represented. Four days after the meeting, Blyton sent the text of the first two Noddy books to her publisher, to be forwarded to van der Beek.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noddy_(character)#cite_note-FOOTNOTEStoney2011loc._2444%E2%80%932463-4"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf4 \super \strokec4 [4]}}\
The Noddy books became one of Blyton's most successful and best-known series, and were hugely popular in the 1950s.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noddy_(character)#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPalmer2013130-5"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf4 \super \strokec4 [5]}}\'a0An extensive range of sub-series, spin-offs and strip books was produced throughout the decade, including\'a0
\f1\i Noddy's Library
\f0\i0 ,\'a0
\f1\i Noddy's Garage of Books
\f0\i0 ,\'a0
\f1\i Noddy's Castle of Books
\f0\i0 ,\'a0
\f1\i Noddy's Toy Station of Books
\f0\i0 \'a0and\'a0
\f1\i Noddy's Shop of Books
\f0\i0 .{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noddy_(character)#cite_note-Noddy_books-6"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf4 \super \strokec4 [6]}}\
The first television adaptation of Noddy called\'a0
\f1\i The Adventures of Noddy
\f0\i0 \'a0was first broadcast in 1955, which was narrated by Enid Blyton.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noddy_(character)#cite_note-EBSChrono-1"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cf4 \super \strokec4 [1]}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noddy_(character)#cite_note-7"}}{\fldrslt 
